deltas.text: An inductor stores energy in the form of an magnetic field.
Its ability to store energy (inductance) is measured in Henries.
This circuit is currently disconnected, so no current is flowing through the inductor.
An inductor obeys the relation V=L*dI/dt, where V is the voltage across the inductor, L is the inductance, and I is the current through the inductor.
When this circuit connects, the inductor will begin charging. As the magnetic field becomes stronger in the inductor, the current through it will increase.
After some time, the inductor has charged to the point where the voltage across it is negligible.
In general, after an inductor has charged for 'a long time', it can be considered a short circuit for purposes of analysis.
The energy stored (different from power!) in an inductor is equal to LI^2/2, in this case, 57.6 J. [END]
